<subSubSection id="A8D5656DA70AD667798D684ADEAB43C4" lastPageId="7" lastPageNumber="85" pageId="6" pageNumber="84" type="description">
<paragraph id="E07036E6A70AD666798D684ADE7E45B3" blockId="6.[189,334,1895,1921]" box="[189,334,1895,1921]" pageId="6" pageNumber="84">
<heading id="BB38818AA70AD666798D684ADE7E45B3" bold="true" box="[189,334,1895,1921]" fontSize="11" level="3" pageId="6" pageNumber="84" reason="3">
<emphasis id="D2BBEAF4A70AD666798D684ADE7E45B3" bold="true" box="[189,334,1895,1921]" pageId="6" pageNumber="84">Description</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="E07036E6A70AD667798D68B8DEAB43C4" blockId="6.[189,1399,1941,2003]" lastBlockId="7.[187,1400,265,502]" lastPageId="7" lastPageNumber="85" pageId="6" pageNumber="84">
Medium sized spiders. Cephalothorax longer than wide, eye field shorter than 50% of total cephalothorax length. PME mid-way between anterior and posterior laterals. Abdomen egg-shaped, beige to brown with a lighter pattern. Chelicerae unident with 2 promarginal teeth and 1 retromarginal tooth. RTA not prominent; cymbium in some species with apical process; tegulum oval, expands beyond apical border of tibia (PLP); embolus stout, set laterally on top of tegulum, wider base. Female epigyne moderately sclerotized, strongly haired. CD well sclerotized, straight, curved or coiled. Spermatheca one-chambered, oval to kidney-shaped. FD is well sclerotized. Accessory glands on external spermathecal walls. Legs I and II robust with scopulae, III and IV more delicate. Hairs and bristles blackish. Leg formula: 1-2-4-3 (
<bibRefCitation id="845E4B17A70BD66779F56EF1DEBE43C4" author="Jastrzebski P." box="[197,398,476,502]" pageId="7" pageNumber="85" pagination="1 - 9" refId="ref13287" refString="Jastrzebski P. 1999. Salticidae from the Himalaya: the genus Carrhotus Thorell 1891 (Araneae, Salticidae). Senckenbergiana Biologica 9: 1 - 9." type="journal article" year="1999">Jastrzebski 1999</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
